question_text: Which statement best describes the central idea of the passage?
options: Mary Oliver was an obscure poet who wrote darkly emotional poems.
Mary Oliver was an influential poet who was inspired by nature and her childhood memories.
Mary Oliver was a well-known poet who wrote for the sake of popular appeal.
Mary Oliver was a famous poet who built her career out of writing poems to please critics.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 3.

Most days, even in old age, she could be found walking through the woods, a dog by her side, and a pen and notebook in her hand.

What role does this sentence play in the overall structure of the passage?
options: It highlights how her love of animals is equal to her passion for writing.
It goes into detail about the process Oliver uses to create beautiful poetry.
It indicates a transition from discussing Oliver's professional career to her personal relationship to poetry.
It contrasts her daily life in old age against the activities of her youth.

question_text: Why does Oliver compare poetry to "a thousand opening doors" in paragraph 4?
options: It highlights how Oliver saw poetry as a way to explore the world.
It demonstrates how Oliver's style of poetry worked their way into her everyday conversations.
It emphasizes the numerous interpretations that a single poem can inspire.
It shows how Oliver saw poetry as a way meet new people in her neighborhood.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 4.

Poetry was, for her, not so much a means of self-expression as much as self-exploration, and eventually self-realization

Which excerpt from paragraph 5 best supports the ideas in this sentence?
options: "This desire to escape to another world was due, in part, to her upbringing."
"It was a very dark and broken house that I came from,' she said in a radio interview."
"Her home life, she said, made her want to be invisible; she took to the woods to disappear."
"Amongst the trees, she appeared to herself. She discovered that she had a voice."

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 5.

The trees were her cathedral; venturing forth under the shelter of branches and leaves, she would find physical and spiritual renewal.

How does the metaphor "the trees were her cathedral" affect the tone of the passage?
options: by creating a sense of familiarity as she saw the shape of her church in the tree branches
by highlighting her desperation to find a spiritual place of protection
by emphasizing the sense of comfort, safety, and wonder that she discovered in nature
by demonstrating her sorrow at the way her parents neglected

question_text: Which sentence from paragraph 6 best supports the central idea of the passage?
options: "In the swoop and grace of a single swan, Ms. Oliver found deeper meaning; from her personal pain and confusion, she found a beautiful perspective to share with the world."
"Ms. Oliver recounts the sight of a swan, drifting on a river and then taking flight, 'an armful of white blossoms."
"The description concludes with the bird, aloft in the air, 'And did you feel it, in your heart"
"In the woods, Ms. Oliver also found faith."

category: Reading Comprehension: Author's Point of View
question_text: The author would most likely agree with which statement?
options: Poets can be inspirational and successful regardless of their age.
Writing every day is a guaranteed path to a successful poetic career.
The opinion of critics is not as important as the reaction of the majority of society.
A poet should follow personal interests and not be influenced by the expectations of others.

category: Reading Comprehension Fiction: Development of Plot
question_text:
Read paragraph 4 from the excerpt.

"My essay! What do you mean?" exclaimed Gwen, as she snatched back her exercise book like a mother clutching her first-born.

The simile used in the sentence contributes to the development of the plot by
options: revealing Gwen's motivation for writing the essay.
showing how deeply Gwen is emotionally invested in her essay.
illustrating the quality of Gwen's essay through the envy it inspired in others.
demonstrating the fragility of Gwen's confidence in herself as a writer.

question_text: What conclusion is best supported by the dialogue in paragraph 13?
options: Netta will say anything to get her way.
Netta has cheated in the past in order to win.
Netta is insecure about her own academic abilities.
Netta has a strong sense of fairness and wants to do the right thing.

category: Reading Comprehension Fiction: Development of Plot
question_text: How does paragraph 24 contribute to the development of the plot?
options: It reveals that Gwen and Netta were never friends, and will never be friends again.
It demonstrates that Netta would rather cheat than work hard at getting a good grade on the essay.
It marks the moment where Gwen makes a difficult decision which leads to misery.
It shows that Gwen would rather get in trouble with Miss Roscoe than let Netta win a prized possession.

question_text: Which sentence best supports the idea that Gwen cares deeply about how others perceive her?
options: "I don't quite see the fairness myself." (paragraph 10)
"Yes, I will! I don't care a bit that I went into her room too. You broke the china, and you'd get into the worst trouble. It wouldn't be pleasant for you." (paragraph 19)
"It was to have brought her such credit from Miss Roscoe, for even if it did not win the prize, it would surely be highly praised." (paragraph 25)
"To Gwen, not the lightest part of the business was that she was faced with the horrible necessity of writing another essay."(paragraph 27)

question_text: All of the following are reasons why Gwen cooperates with Netta EХСЕРТ
options: "I've been uncommonly patient with you, but I don't quite appreciate the joke of being cheated out of that money. I must either have the money or its equivalent." (paragraph 15)
"She was a jolly enough fair-weather comrade, but she could be uncommonly nasty if things went wrong."(paragraph 16)
"Well, it just amounts to this: if you don't choose, I'll tell Miss Roscoe."(paragraph 19)

"Neither brilliant nor a hard worker, she had no opportunity of distinguishing herself in the class under ordinary circumstances: here chance had flung into her hand the very thing she wanted." (paragraph 26)

question_text: How do the consequences of Gwen's agreement with Netta show the theme of the excerpt?
options: It reveals the downsides of dishonesty, as Gwen had to do twice as much work as a result of not telling the truth.
It highlights the importance of not leaving things to the last minute, as Gwen didn't have time to do a good job on her second essay.
It shows how wishes can be dangerous, Gwen's desire for attention led to her punishment by the Principal.
It emphasizes the strength of friendship, as Netta eventually returns the essay to a distraught Gwen.

question_text: Which of the following sentences best supports the narrator's description of Netta from paragraph 26?
options: "'I had hoped the average results would be higher,' commented the Principal. 'Very few girls have treated the subject with any real effort.'" (paragraph 29)
"You thoroughly deserve the prize which I offered, and I have written your name in the book."(paragraph 29)
"Each girl looked at her neighbor in almost incredulous astonishment." (paragraph 30)
"Gwen drew her breath hard and clenched her fists till her nails hurt her palms." (paragraph 31)

question_text:
Read paragraph 31 from the excerpt.

Gwen drew her breath hard and clenched her fists till her nails hurt her palms.

How does this sentence contribute to the tone of the end of the excerpt?
options: It shows a sorrowful tone, as Gwen realizes her actions would have disappointed her father.
It creates a righteous tone, as Gwen sacrificed her chance to receive praise so that someone else could experience.
It highlights a fearful tone, as Gwen is worries someone will find out about her arrangement with Netta.
It reinforces a frustrated tone, as Gwen is unable to claim authorship to her winning essay.

question_text: Which statement best describes the central idea of the passage?
options: "One of the most powerful earthquakes ever recorded in the area struck San Francisco at 5:12 a.m. of April 18, 1906."(paragraph 2)
"Though many of the fires were started as a direct result of the earthquake, many more happened days after the first rumblings." (paragraph 4)
"The U.S. House and Senate Appropriations committee quickly sent funds to supply residents with food, water, tents, blankets, and medical supplies." (paragraph 7)
"Eventually, San Francisco recovered from the devastation of 1906, going on to enjoy decades of geological peace." (paragraph 9)

question_text: The map supports a central idea of paragraphs 1-2 by
options: indicating the extent of the damage caused by the quake to the west coast of Canada and the United States.
proving that the earthquake of San Francisco was caused by man-made factors.
showing the population decreases by geographical location after the quake.
demonstrating how San Francisco was located squarely on top of the San Andreas fault line.

category: Reading Comprehension: Author's Point of View
question_text: With which statement would the author ofthis excerpt most likely agree?
options: The geography around San Francisco returned to its original form in the span of several months.
The earthquake of San Francisco caused great damage due to its sustained length.
The damages caused by the earthquake to the city of San Francisco have become exaggerated over time.
The recorded strength of the earthquake may not be precisely accurate due to less advanced technology at the time.

question_text: How did the author's use of sequencing in paragraph 2 contribute to the mood of the paragraph?
options: It shows the atmosphere of confusion as people attempted to identify what caused the quake.
It highlights the feeling of terror that people must have felt during the quake, as it wreaked devastation extremely quickly.
It reveals the sense of efficiency that characterized how government officials planned their response to the quake.
It creates a sense of boredom as it gives an in-depth scientific overview of the geological aspects of the quake.

question_text: Which statement best describes the firefighters' experience in putting out the flames caused by the quake?
options: They were extremely efficient and experienced in how they approached the problem.
They lacked organization and as a result failed to solve the problem.
They caused additional damage to the city in their efforts to solve the problem.
They educated local people on ways to prevent a repeat of the problem.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 5.

The fire did not discriminate, taking from the city even knowledge; the California Academy of Science, which housed a large botanical collection, went up in flames.

How does the word choice in this sentence contribute to the overall meaning of the excerpt?
options: It personifies the fire as relentlessly burning through the city's treasures.
It creates a chaotic atmosphere, mimicking the experience of city inhabitants during the initial shocks.
It shows that trees and wood-based infrastructures were particularly vulnerable to the fire.
It highlights how the fire intentionally targeted places of learning and knowledge.

question_text: Which statement best supports the idea that the government effectively responded to people's needs after the quake?
options: "However, after large quantitics of Army clothing was passed out, they quickly saw that food and shelter were the main concerns." (paragraph 6)
"The U.S. House and Senate Appropriations committee quickly sent funds to supply residents with food, water, tents, blankets, and medical supplies." (paragraph 7)
"Though the fires died out and the smoke cleared within a few days, it took several months for San Francisco to reorganize and begin reconstruction of lives and buildings." (paragraph 8)
"In the end, insurance companies estimated losses at over $200 million, the equivalent of $6 billion today." (paragraph 8)

question_text: What role does paragraph 9 play in the structure of the overall passage?
options: It describes the experiences of San Francisco with repeated earthquakes in subsequent years.
It emphasizes the long reaching impact of the earthquake on San Francisco's infrastructures and geography.
It provides a sense of closure to the narrative style of the events that happened during the earthquake.
It critiques the way city officials of San Francisco responded to the emergency, and offered suggestions for future improvements.

question_text: Which statement best describes the central idea of the passage?
options: Learning things by rote memorization is essential for high performance on standardized tests.
Learning things by rote memorization can be helpful on some standardized tests but does not lead to skills that are useful after leaving the school environment.
Learning things by rote memorization is more efficient than learning how to think critically.
Learning things by rote memorization will eventually lead to the development of critical thinking skills.

question_text:
Read this excerpt from paragraph 2.

Ask a typical middle schooler how to find the missing side of a right triangle, and he or she will hopefully recite the Pythagorean Theorem. But go one step further and ask the reason why it works, and most students will fumble for an explanation.

What is the most likely reason the author included this example?
options: to illustrate a drawback to rote memorization of information by using a familiar example
to highlight students' lack of math knowledge by showing how they lack basic knowledge of formulas
to explain how critical thinking skills would help students remember math concepts
to give step-by-step directions of what can be done to improve test scores

question_text: In paragraph 3, the word "pitfalls" is used to highligh
options: how rote memorization is an obviously dangerous method of teaching and learning.
how rote memorization can have unexpected drawbacks for students despite appearing beneficial.
that students may trip and stumble if they are too focused on memorizing information while traveling.
that critical thinking skills can trap students into a repetitive and rigid way of thinking.

question_text: The author most likely included the study by the U.S. Department of Education in paragraph 4 to
options: offer evidence to support the main claim of the paragraph.
explain that rote memorization can help students be more successful
provide a counterargument to common arguments against the claim.
highlight the universal nature of the main problem identified in the passage.

question_text:
Read this excerpt from paragraph 5.

After all, the human brain is not designed like a computer. Where computers more effectively store and retrieve information, the human mind demonstrates a greater ability to reason and process complex information.

What is the most likely reason the author compares human brains to computers?
options: to introduce the similarities between human brain structure and circuitry paths in computers
to conclude that computers are superior to human minds in their ability to reason and process information
to emphasize the ways in which human brains are specialized and distinct from computers
to provide an example of how rote memorization can make the human mind become computerlike in its processes

question_text: What role does paragraph 6 play in the overall structure of the passage?
options: It contrasts the short-term benefits ofcritical thinking with those of rote memorization.
It reinforces the long-term benefits of developing critical thinking skills in students.
It highlights how rote memorization can help students become better critical thinkers.
It explains various methods that instructors can use to foster the development of critical thinking skills.

question_text: Which statement best supports the idea that the development of critical thinking skills will assist students in life beyond school?
options: "The recall of this information can be easily assessed by standardized tests." (paragraph 4)
"Instead, we should be developing our students' conceptual understanding." (paragraph 5)
"Regardless of the subject being taught, all teachers should provide opportunities for students to ask questions." (paragraph 7)
"The sharing of ideas with peers helps students become open to new perspectives. It also fosters empathy and tolerance of different opinions."(paragraph 9)

question_text: What is the most likely reason that the author uses the word "crazy" in paragraph 9?
options: to point out one of the few negative aspects of brainstorming in the classroom
to warn teachers about the problems associated with teaching critical thinking skills
to acknowledge the often unconventional yet beneficial outcomes of critical thinking
to question the overemphasis on rote memorization in traditional classroom teaching
